 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cross  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cross","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived near a cross, such as one set up by the roadside or in a marketplace, from Middle English <i>cros</i> (Old English <i>cros</i> and Old Norse <i>kross</i>, ultimately from Latin <i>crux</i>, <i>crucem</i>). It is commonly Latinized in medieval records as <i>ad crucem</i> and <i>de Cruce</i> but examples of this can just as well belong to the synonymous but less common name   Crouch  . In a few cases the surname may have been given originally to someone who lived by a crossroads, but this sense of the word seems to have been a comparatively late development. In other cases, the surname (and its European cognates; see 3 below) may have denoted someone who carried the cross in processions of the Christian Church, but in English at least the usual word for this sense was   Crozier  .","Irish: shortened form of   McCrossen  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cross’ or ‘the cross’, such as French   Lacroix  , German   Kreutz  , and Slovenian and Croatian <b>Križ</b> (see   Kriz  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Crosse was born about 1351, in Harrington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1377, in Liverpool, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 27."},"et":{"Abt. 1351–1377":"umbes 1351–1377","1377–1425":"1377–1425","1351–1377":"1351–1377","1425":"1425","1377":"1377","1351":"1351","Abt. 1351":"umbes 1351","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harrington, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrington, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1351–1377":"noin 1351–1377","1377–1425":"1377–1425","1351–1377":"1351–1377","1425":"1425","1377":"1377","1351":"1351","Abt. 1351":"noin 1351","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Harrington, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrington, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt. 1351–1377":"environ 1351–1377","1377–1425":"1377–1425","1351–1377":"1351–1377","1425":"1425","1377":"1377","1351":"1351","Abt. 1351":"environ 1351","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Harrington, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrington, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Crosse est né environ 1351, à Harrington, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1377, à Liverpool, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 27 ans."},"de":{"Abt. 1351–1377":"um 1351–1377","1377–1425":"1377–1425","1351–1377":"1351–1377","1425":"1425","1377":"1377","1351":"1351","Abt. 1351":"um 1351","Liverpool, Lancashire, England":"Liverpool, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Harrington, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"William Crosse wurde um 1351 in Harrington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb 1377 im Alter von 27 Jahren in Liverpool, Lancashire, England, Un